WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.450 --> 00:00:13.225
Start with pi interlingua. Pi groups are physics
balance clues. They translate rain, sunlight,
flushing, and decay into numbers that can be compared
across different coasts without copying the beach
answer.

2
00:00:17.450 --> 00:00:28.800
Here is the whole machine. The fetcher brings public
data in, the lakehouse organizes it, transforms turn
it into clues, target engines ask fair questions,
models compete, and evidence gates decide what
survives.

3
00:00:29.450 --> 00:00:41.925
The fetcher is the front door for data. It can list
sources, discover what is available, dry-run a plan,
fetch or resume downloads, and validate the result
before anything becomes a trusted table.

4
00:00:45.450 --> 00:00:59.150
The fetcher grows through the registry. A new source
adds a SourceSpec and either a custom adapter or a
generic fetch plan. Then it uses the same buttons and
creates the same manifest, coverage, and validation
artifacts.

5
00:01:00.450 --> 00:01:13.800
Raw data lands safely first. Beach lab samples,
weather, sensors, water quality, and research feeds
arrive before we change names, units, or dates. This
keeps a copy of what the outside world actually gave
us.

6
00:01:14.450 --> 00:01:25.125
The lakehouse has three shelves. Bronze keeps the
original files. Silver holds cleaned tables. Gold
stores model runs, predictions, metrics, and
leaderboards.

7
00:01:27.450 --> 00:01:36.325
Transforms are the cleanup team. They fix units, match
stations, join sources by time and place, and build
features that a model can use.

8
00:01:40.450 --> 00:01:52.275
Leakage is cheating by accident. If a feature uses
tomorrow to explain today, or chooses columns using
the test period, the model gets an unfair answer key.
The firewall blocks that.

9
00:01:57.450 --> 00:02:08.650
The folders act like rooms in a school lab. Source-
shaped datasets, silver tables, gold results, research
engines, reports, and the explainer website each have
a clear home.

10
00:02:09.450 --> 00:02:20.175
Feature builders turn tables into useful clues: recent
history, rain and runoff, physics pi groups, tensor
factors, and oxygen covariates for stress screening.

11
00:02:22.450 --> 00:02:37.600
Tensorification is the four-dimensional part. We stack
sparse signals by time, source, variable, and view.
The factorization looks for shared state patterns
across that cube, then only scoped, leakage-safe
factors can support claims.

12
00:02:42.450 --> 00:02:54.000
Each target engine asks one exact question. Beach
bacteria, surprise-onset events, oxygen stress,
harmful algae signals, and state QA each use its own
grading rule.

13
00:02:55.450 --> 00:03:06.800
Then the model engines compete on that target. Simple
logistic models, tree boosters, neural nets, tensor
factorization, and zero-shot readouts all get graded
against honest baselines.

14
00:03:07.450 --> 00:03:18.325
A result is not trusted just because it looks good.
Holdout tests, baselines, confidence intervals, null
checks, calibration, and critic reviews decide what
survives.

15
00:03:19.450 --> 00:03:32.650
The honesty gate is a gauntlet. First test on unseen
time or place. Then beat the boring baseline. Then ask
whether luck explains it. Then check leakage. Then let
a critic try to break the claim.

16
00:03:39.450 --> 00:03:53.800
Finding one: in tested held-out coastal datasets,
fixed physics clues ranked bacteria risk better than
normal-rate guessing. That is useful for first-pass
triage in similar daily bacteria data, not official
advisories.

17
00:03:56.450 --> 00:04:08.975
Finding two: on the California surprise-onset slice,
the model helped spot recently clean beach days that
later turned dirty. That is a scoped clean-to-dirty
claim, not every bacteria forecast.

18
00:04:13.450 --> 00:04:25.825
Finding three: low-oxygen stress can be screened from
other water-quality clues. This is useful when oxygen
sensors are sparse, but it is still a screening lane
that needs workflow and calibration.

19
00:04:30.450 --> 00:04:42.950
Finding four: tensor patterns helped check and fill
one tide-density sensor signal. That is useful for
data quality and state reconstruction, not a customer
bacteria warning model by itself.

20
00:04:47.450 --> 00:04:58.450
Finding five: the generic foundation-model story was
dropped. Bigger learned features did not beat simpler
physics under fair gates, so the public story should
not sell that claim.

21
00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:11.800
Bottom line: the win is not magic AI. It is careful
data plumbing, physics translation, leakage control,
and honesty gates that show what held, what failed,
and where the boundary is.

